edu.caltech.nanodb.sqlparse

Class NanoSqlLexer

  • java.lang.Object
    • antlr.CharScanner
      • edu.caltech.nanodb.sqlparse.NanoSqlLexer
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    antlr.TokenStream, NanoSqlParserTokenTypes
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    InteractiveClient.InteractiveLexer

    public class NanoSqlLexer
extends antlr.CharScanner
implements NanoSqlParserTokenTypes, antlr.TokenStream
    A lexer for tokenizing SQL commands into various tokens necessary for parsing. As is true for most lexers generated by ANTLR, this one primarily concentrates on identifying various symbols like punctuation characters, whitespace, and newlines, although it also identifies some more "high-level" tokens such as identifiers and "typed" literals (i.e. literals that follow a well-defined format based on their type).

    All of the SQL-specific keywords are actually declared in the parser, so that keeps the lexer definition pretty short and sweet.

      • mNUM_LITERAL_OR_SYMBOL

        public final void mNUM_LITERAL_OR_SYMBOL(boolean _createToken)
                                  throws antlr.RecognitionException,
                                         antlr.CharStreamException,
                                         antlr.TokenStreamException
        Number-literal parsing is tricky, because you might have an integer, a decimal number, or a simple period ('.') by itself. This lexer rule handles all three of these options, and sets the token-type appropriately.

        Note that these numbers are unsigned. Signed numbers have to be processed separately.

        Throws:
        antlr.RecognitionException
        antlr.CharStreamException
        antlr.TokenStreamException
